    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Mesembryanthemum acinaciforme</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9420",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Well-known, large, abundant coastal plant forming long, creeping stems bearing stout, curved green or red-tinged leaves that are triangular in cross section (hence scimitar-shapes or ‘acinaciform’).</p><p>Large, flat flowers encircled with many radiating petals are produced in spring and summer and are magenta (purplish-red) in colour. The fruits are like a spinning top enclosed in a winged stalk and become wrinkled and leathery with age. Internally the many small seeds are enclosed in a sticky jelly.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9421",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Stems can be many meters long, leaves from 60-130 mm long and flowers up to 100 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9422",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Yzerfontein to Mossel Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9423",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Well known plant forming extensive mats in sandy areas along the coast, where it often grown adjacent to and is confused with the better-known yellow-flowered sour fig <i>C. edulis</i>. Popular as a garden plant in coastal areas and has been introduced to South-West England, where it has become naturalised.</p><p>An ecologically significant species that provides shelter and habitat to numerous species including snails, reptiles and many insects. The flowers are pollinated by a variety of bees and beetles and flowers and fruits are eaten by rodents, antelope, porcupines and baboons. The leaves are also eaten by tortoises.</p><p>The edible fruit are widely collected to make a popular tart jam. Various parts of the plant are also used in traditional medicine. Preparations of the fruit are taken orally for the treatment of tuberculosis and other pulmonary infections. Leaf juice is applied to sores or burn/scald wounds and used as antiseptic. Preparations of leaf juice, taken orally, are said to be diuretic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9424",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9425",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers August to December.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9426",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are several similar species in this and related genera. Frequently confused with the sour fig <i>C. edulis</i> which is also a large trailing species with a similar range and habitat preferences, but which has yellow flowers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9427",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
